Let's reconsider the standard interpretation of such physics problems. Usually, they ask for the **time difference** between the two people arriving at the destination.
Let's assume the question asks: **What is the time difference between Person 1 arriving at 40/F and Person 2 arriving at 40/F?**
If Person 2 stops at $X$ ($X \neq 40$), the lift goes 1/F $\to$ $X$ $\to$ 40/F.
Time for Person 2 to reach 40/F = Time for 1/F $\to$ $X$ + Time for $X$ $\to$ 40/F.
Time for 1/F $\to$ $X$ = $t_{acc} + t_{const} + t_{dec\_to\_X}$.
Time for $X$ $\to$ 40/F = $t_{acc} + t_{const} + t_{dec\_to\_40}$.
Total Time = $2 \times (t_{acc} + t_{const}) + t_{dec\_to\_X}$.
This seems overly complex and unlikely to be the intended simple answer.

